 practical knowledge through allegory and storytelling, and as such, it has little use for formal written language. This lack of physical books and scrolls has been interpreted by some anthropologists from other cultures as a sign of lesser intelligence; but these scholars have clearly not had to perfectly memorize and recite an hours-long epic poem they have never seen written down.";}i:2;i:1224;}i:32;a:3:{i:0;s:17:"listcontent_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:1666;}i:33;a:3:{i:0;s:14:"listitem_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:1666;}i:34;a:3:{i:0;s:13:"listitem_open";i:1;a:1:{i:0;i:1;}i:2;i:1666;}i:35;a:3:{i:0;s:16:"listcontent_open";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:1666;}i:36;a:3:{i:0;s:5:"cdata";i:1;a:1:{i:0;s:558:" Orcs are a tribal, nomadic race. They usually engage peacefully with other Orcish tribes they come across; so peacefully, in fact, that they have had to make a habit of engaging in non-lethal combat and mock war games with the other tribes in order to keep them sharp in preparation for a real threat. These events have become a point of great pride for the Orcs, who take winning them very seriously. The outside observer might be forgiven for mistaking their deep enthusiasm for this common practice as never-ending civil wars fueled by simple bloodlust. ";}i:2;i:1670;}i:37;a:3:{i:0;s:17:"listcontent_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2228;}i:38;a:3:{i:0;s:14:"listitem_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2228;}i:39;a:3:{i:0;s:13:"listitem_open";i:1;a:1:{i:0;i:1;}i:2;i:2228;}i:40;a:3:{i:0;s:16:"listcontent_open";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2228;}i:41;a:3:{i:0;s:5:"cdata";i:1;a:1:{i:0;s:316:" Given their nomadic nature, Orcs also have few permanent cities. Again, non-native anthropologists may see this as a lack of technological progress, but the Orcs have found ways to produce just as much economic output and wealth as the other races, only they don't have to permanently change the landscape to do it.";}i:2;i:2232;}i:42;a:3:{i:0;s:17:"listcontent_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2548;}i:43;a:3:{i:0;s:14:"listitem_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2548;}i:44;a:3:{i:0;s:13:"listitem_open";i:1;a:1:{i:0;i:1;}i:2;i:2548;}i:45;a:3:{i:0;s:16:"listcontent_open";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2548;}i:46;a:3:{i:0;s:5:"cdata";i:1;a:1:{i:0;s:402:" In much the same way that traditional Mongolian culture centers around horses for work, food, materials, and companionship; Orcs raise lions. It is not uncommon to see even young Orcish children raising a lion cub that will be with them for most of their life. And there are certainly few things more intimidating than staring down a formation of well-trained Orcs riding full-grown lions into combat.";}i:2;i:2552;}i:47;a:3:{i:0;s:17:"listcontent_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2954;}i:48;a:3:{i:0;s:14:"listitem_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2954;}i:49;a:3:{i:0;s:13:"listitem_open";i:1;a:1:{i:0;i:1;}i:2;i:2954;}i:50;a:3:{i:0;s:16:"listcontent_open";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:2954;}i:51;a:3:{i:0;s:5:"cdata";i:1;a:1:{i:0;s:277:" Orcs are also very musical in nature. Song lends itself well to their oral teachings, and Orcish bards are actually more common than most people think. Particularly traditional Orcs often play the morin khuur: a tall stringed instrument most closely related to a large fiddle.";}i:2;i:2958;}i:52;a:3:{i:0;s:17:"listcontent_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:3235;}i:53;a:3:{i:0;s:14:"listitem_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:3235;}i:54;a:3:{i:0;s:11:"listu_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:3235;}i:55;a:3:{i:0;s:13:"section_close";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:3235;}i:56;a:3:{i:0;s:12:"document_end";i:1;a:0:{}i:2;i:3235;}}